Review saved. Here's a summary of the findings for `nsqd/channel.go`:

**8 findings** (5 BUG, 3 QUESTION) — **FIX FIRST**

| # | Type | Severity | Lines | Description |
|---|------|----------|-------|-------------|
| 1 | BUG | High | 563-565 | `processInFlightQueue` uses `goto exit` on race, aborting all remaining timed-out message processing |
| 2 | BUG | High | 534-536 | `processDeferredQueue` — same `goto exit` sibling bug |
| 3 | BUG | Medium | 278-290 | `PutMessage` lacks `exitMutex` guard (unlike `RequeueMessage`), TOCTOU race loses messages on shutdown |
| 4 | BUG | Medium | 309-312 | `PutMessageDeferred` has no exit guard at all — messages silently lost post-shutdown |
| 5 | BUG | Medium | 117-118 | `initPQ` replaces maps without holding `inFlightMutex`/`deferredMutex` — data race when called from `Empty()` |
| 6 | QUESTION | Low | 203-239 | `flush()` iterates maps without mutexes — relies on clients being fully stopped |
| 7 | QUESTION | Low | 163-167 | `client.Close()` may be async — race window before flush |
| 8 | QUESTION | Low | 537 | `put()` error silently discarded in deferred queue processing — message lost on backend failure |

The most impactful bugs are the `goto exit` patterns in both queue processors — under concurrent FIN traffic, a single race causes all remaining timed-out/deferred messages to be skipped until the next scan cycle.
